Given these important differences, then, we are loath to claim that our cross-case comparison can offer a strong test of the causal relationship between candidate selection systems and party cohesion. But we are willing to claim such a comparison offers at least a weak test. The ANC and SWAPO, after all, share many important characteristics. Potential party ‘splitters' face similar structural incentives: in both countries, the cost of a parliamentary seat is low (South Africa and Namibia employ a highly proportionate version of Closed-List PR to elect members of the lower house of parliament);
10
 there is a moderately high number of ethnic groups that might act as a platform to a breakaway party (Posner, 2004: 856); both countries are unitary in nature; and both countries have a highly institutionalized party system. Both parties shared similar parliamentary majorities in the run-up to the 2004 parliamentary elections. In cultural terms, too, a less dissimilar pair of dominant parties would be difficult to find. Finally, the ANC and SWAPO selected candidates in radically different ways.
